>I haven't seen anybody else mention this yet.  In the April 1994 issue
>of Data Communications, page 17, there is a short news item that claims
>that accused double agent Aldrich Ames may have sold information about
>the Clipper initiative to the Russians.  A source is quoted "If there's
>only a 1 percent chance that Clipper has been compromised, the whole
>thing's over, and we have to start from scratch."

Why would a CIA agent have a need-to-know about a specific crypto algorithm?

>Unless Ames actually sold escrowed keys, in which case the whole idea
>of key escrow should be dead as it would be proven to be insecurable.

I wonder how many may have been escrowed prior to his defection?  Also, if a
single person in the government, without a court order, could gain access to
those keys, then the whole scheme needs to be "rethought" anyway.

